<TITLE>Close to Home: The risk of getting too cozy with Russia</TITLE>


<TEXT>
| The ongoing <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">revelations</EVENT> about the presidents potential vulnerability to Russian influence are unprecedented. My personal professional experience may <EVENT eid="e2" class="I_STATE">help</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">place</EVENT> this in some context.

I served for <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DURATION" value="P30Y">30 years</TIMEX3> in the U.S. Foreign Service, from <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="1970">1970</TIMEX3> to <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="2000">2000</TIMEX3>. During <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="X">that</TIMEX3> time, my colleagues and I <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">witnessed</EVENT> the <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">transitions</EVENT> of six U.S. presidents and at least eight secretaries of state. I <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">served</EVENT> at three embassies and two consulates on three continents. I <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">worked</EVENT> with intelligence officers at every post, and I <EVENT eid="e8" class="I_STATE">think</EVENT> it will be <EVENT eid="e9" class="I_STATE">useful</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">offer</EVENT> a brief <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">description</EVENT> of that function at a U.S. overseas mission.

Simply stated, the purpose of intelligence gathering is to <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">provide</EVENT> our government with as much information about foreign governments and their policies and intentions as possible. Contrary to some <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">current</TIMEX3> <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">perceptions</EVENT>, this cannot be <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">done</EVENT> solely using technology. Bugs and drones cannot <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">reveal</EVENT> intentions. Ultimately, there is no substitute for information <EVENT eid="e16" class="I_ACTION">provided</EVENT> by human beings in positions to <EVENT eid="e17" class="I_ACTION">provide</EVENT> it.

How this is attained is not just the stuff of Hollywood  and the end of the Cold War has not <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">changed</EVENT> anything. In general, all national intelligence agencies <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">function</EVENT> similarly. Foreign government officials, businessmen, academicians and media figures are all targets.

I <EVENT eid="e20" class="I_ACTION">worked</EVENT> with CIA officers whose task was to <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">identify</EVENT> host country nationals who were in positions, or who might <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">attain</EVENT> positions later, in which they had information useful or vital to our national security. The process of <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">identifying</EVENT> possible sources might <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">take</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DURATION" value="PXM">months</TIMEX3>, or years, but once <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">identified</EVENT> as a likely source, a different officer, <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">sent</EVENT> from Washington would <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">make</EVENT> the "pitch." Should the target refuse, he or she was thus not able to <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">identify</EVENT> who initially <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">identified</EVENT> him or her.

During the Cold War, ideology was frequently the motivation for recruiting, but if the target was <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">considered</EVENT> sufficiently important, money and other incentives would be <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">offered</EVENT>. Creating a compromising situation could be <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">used</EVENT> if necessary, and pure <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">blackmail</EVENT> was the ultimate option. Such a trap could be <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">initiated</EVENT> in a mundane fashion: dinner. Sports tickets. A bottle of Scotch. Even a small loan for a vacation. We were <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">trained</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e36" class="I_STATE">expected</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e37" class="OCCURRENCE">report</EVENT> even the most trivial contact.

Marital problems and tax or financial issues were vulnerable areas, but the idea that any of the gifts were <EVENT eid="e38" class="OCCURRENCE">offered</EVENT> because "they must <EVENT eid="e39" class="OCCURRENCE">like</EVENT> me" would be <EVENT eid="e40" class="OCCURRENCE">greeted</EVENT> with <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">scorn</EVENT> or hilarity. In the very rare event that one was <EVENT eid="e42" class="OCCURRENCE">compromised</EVENT> and sensitive information was <EVENT eid="e43" class="OCCURRENCE">requested</EVENT>, there were two obvious reactions: One was to <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">roll</EVENT> over and <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">submit</EVENT> to being <EVENT eid="e46" class="OCCURRENCE">used</EVENT> in hopes the material would never be <EVENT eid="e47" class="OCCURRENCE">used</EVENT>. The other was to <EVENT eid="e48" class="OCCURRENCE">deny</EVENT> the <EVENT eid="e49" class="OCCURRENCE">accusations</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e50" class="I_ACTION">try</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e51" class="OCCURRENCE">denigrate</EVENT> the source of the charges and demand that the source be <EVENT eid="e52" class="OCCURRENCE">revealed</EVENT>.

Regarding sources, Im <EVENT eid="e53" class="I_ACTION">amazed</EVENT> at the <EVENT eid="e54" class="OCCURRENCE">reluctance</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e55" class="OCCURRENCE">understand</EVENT> why such sources <EVENT eid="e56" class="I_STATE">need</EVENT> to be <EVENT eid="e57" class="OCCURRENCE">protected</EVENT> and not made public. Revealing the source not only <EVENT eid="e58" class="OCCURRENCE">ends</EVENT> the sources usefulness and makes it more difficult to persuade others in <TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DATE" value="FUTURE_REF">the future</TIMEX3>, but it also <EVENT eid="e59" class="OCCURRENCE">reveals</EVENT> how the information was <EVENT eid="e60" class="OCCURRENCE">acquired</EVENT>. Even the legendary Enigma/Ultra code breakers <EVENT eid="e61" class="I_ACTION">allowed</EVENT> setbacks and even loss of life to <EVENT eid="e62" class="OCCURRENCE">protect</EVENT> a source that was so irreplaceable.

If any of this <EVENT eid="e63" class="OCCURRENCE">sets</EVENT> off alarm bells, it should. For a foreign intelligence officer, <EVENT eid="e64" class="OCCURRENCE">compromising</EVENT> a senior U.S. government official, let alone the head of state, would be considered a virtual <EVENT eid="e65" class="OCCURRENCE">fantasy</EVENT>. But what I have <EVENT eid="e66" class="OCCURRENCE">described</EVENT> above is the precise <EVENT eid="e67" class="OCCURRENCE">work</EVENT> that Vladimir Putin did for <TIMEX3 tid="t8" type="DURATION" value="P30Y">30 years</TIMEX3>.

Dean Dizikes <EVENT eid="e68" class="OCCURRENCE">worked</EVENT> for <TIMEX3 tid="t9" type="DURATION" value="P1E">three decades</TIMEX3> in the U.S. foreign service, <EVENT eid="e69" class="OCCURRENCE">serving</EVENT> in embassies in Germany, Iran and other countries. He lives in Petaluma.
</TEXT>


